               <note>
                  <ab type="description">The town of Gondar is located in today's North Gondar Zone
                     (historically <placeName ref="LOC1713Bagemd">Bagemdǝr</placeName> province) in the
                        <placeName ref="LOC1426Amhara">Amhara Regional State</placeName>. It evolved
                     from an obscure 17th century market town into the flourishing capital of the
                     Ethiopian monarchy, passed through an era of decline and destruction and
                     underwent a slow renaissance in the mid-20th century. It is today one of the
                     largest cities in Ethiopia. Gondar started to flourish after aṣe <persName
                        ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> chose Gondar as his camp to
                     control the collection of customs on the <placeName ref="LOC5339RedSea">Red
                        Sea</placeName> - <placeName ref="LOC5888Tana"> Ṭana</placeName> -
                        <placeName ref="LOC2966Ennary">Ǝnnarya</placeName> trade routes. By the late
                     17th century, Gondar had become a permanent and sizeable settlement where Ethiopians' rulers resided
                     when not campaigning and where the highest commerical, political and religious
                     classes gathered around the throne.</ab>
               </note>
            </place>
